        "text": "Third solution. (Communicated by Noam Elkies.) Since f is strictly increasing, for some yo, we can de- fine the inverse function g(y) of f for y ≥ yo. Then x = g(f(x)), and we may differentiate to find that 1 = g′(f (x))f (x) = g′(f(x))f (f (x)). It folws that g(y) = 1/ f() for y ≥ yo; since g takes arbitrarily lare values, the integral J dy/ f(y) must diverge. One then gets a contradiction from any reasonable lower bound on f (y) for y large, e.g., the bound f (x) ≥ αx2 from the second solution. (One can also start with a linear lower bound f(x) ≥ βx, then use the integral expresion for to deduce that g(x) ≤ γlogx, which in turn forces f(x) to grow exponentially.)",
